{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WJDyNr2hKt2hiXCZDuSM9R","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information needed. Let me create a comprehensive summary:\n\n## Search Results: Kubernetes Watch Cache Filtering and DELETE Event Handling\n\nBased on my analysis of the Kubernetes v1.9.1 codebase, here are the key files and code sections related to watch cache filtering logic and DELETE event handling with resourceVersion:\n\n### Key Files Located\n\n1. **/workspace/kubernetes/staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/watch_cache.go** - Core watch cache event structure\n2. **/workspace/kubernetes/staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher.go** - Cache watcher filtering and event sending\n3. **/workspace/kubernetes/staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/watcher.go** - ETcd3 watcher with correct resourceVersion handling\n\n---\n\n## 1. Watch Cache Event Structure (watch_cache.go, lines 45-61)\n\nThe `watchCacheEvent` struct includes both current and previous object information:\n\n```go\ntype watchCacheEvent struct {\n    Type                 watch.EventType\n    Object               runtime.Object\n    ObjLabels            labels.Set\n    ObjFields            fields.Set\n    ObjUninitialized     bool\n    PrevObject           runtime.Object\n    PrevObjLabels        labels.Set\n    PrevObjFields        fields.Set\n    PrevObjUninitialized bool\n    Key                  string\n    ResourceVersion      uint64\n}\n```\n\nThe watchCacheEvent stores the ResourceVersion once (the event's RV) but also maintains the PrevObject for filtering purposes.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Watch Cache Filtering Logic (cacher.go, lines 874-894)\n\nThe **sendWatchCacheEvent** function handles the filtering of watch events for individual watchers:\n\n```go\n// NOTE: sendWatchCacheEvent is assumed to not modify <event> !!!\nfunc (c *cacheWatcher) sendWatchCacheEvent(event *watchCacheEvent) {\n    curObjPasses := event.Type != watch.Deleted && c.filter(event.Key, event.ObjLabels, event.ObjFields, event.ObjUninitialized)\n    oldObjPasses := false\n    if event.PrevObject != nil {\n        oldObjPasses = c.filter(event.Key, event.PrevObjLabels, event.PrevObjFields, event.PrevObjUninitialized)\n    }\n    if !curObjPasses && !oldObjPasses {\n        // Watcher is not interested in that object.\n        return\n    }\n\n    var watchEvent watch.Event\n    switch {\n    case curObjPasses && !oldObjPasses:\n        watchEvent = watch.Event{Type: watch.Added, Object: event.Object.DeepCopyObject()}\n    case curObjPasses && oldObjPasses:\n        watchEvent = watch.Event{Type: watch.Modified, Object: event.Object.DeepCopyObject()}\n    case !curObjPasses && oldObjPasses:\n        watchEvent = watch.Event{Type: watch.Deleted, Object: event.PrevObject.DeepCopyObject()}\n    }\n    // ... send watchEvent to client\n}\n```\n\n**Key behavior on DELETE**: When an object no longer passes the filter (line 892), the watcher sends a DELETE event with the **PrevObject** (line 893). This is the old object before the filter stopped matching it.\n\n---\n\n## 3. ETcd3 Watcher - Correct ResourceVersion on DELETE Events (etcd3/watcher.go)\n\nThe etcd3 watcher correctly handles resourceVersion on DELETE events in two places:\n\n### Location A: prepareObjs function (lines 351-379)\n\n```go\nfunc (wc *watchChan) prepareObjs(e *event) (curObj runtime.Object, oldObj runtime.Object, err error) {\n    if !e.isDeleted {\n        data, _, err := wc.watcher.transformer.TransformFromStorage(e.value, ...)\n        curObj, err = decodeObj(wc.watcher.codec, wc.watcher.versioner, data, e.rev)\n    }\n    // We need to decode prevValue, only if this is deletion event or\n    // the underlying filter doesn't accept all objects (otherwise we\n    // know that the filter for previous object will return true and\n    // we need the object only to compute whether it was filtered out\n    // before).\n    if len(e.prevValue) > 0 && (e.isDeleted || !wc.acceptAll()) {\n        data, _, err := wc.watcher.transformer.TransformFromStorage(e.prevValue, ...)\n        // Note that this sends the *old* object with the etcd revision for the time at\n        // which it gets deleted.\n        oldObj, err = decodeObj(wc.watcher.codec, wc.watcher.versioner, data, e.rev)\n    }\n    return curObj, oldObj, nil\n}\n```\n\n**Critical detail** (line 374): The oldObj is decoded with `e.rev` - the DELETE event's revision number.\n\n### Location B: decodeObj function (lines 382-400)\n\n```go\nfunc decodeObj(codec runtime.Codec, versioner storage.Versioner, data []byte, rev int64) (_ runtime.Object, err error) {\n    obj, err := runtime.Decode(codec, []byte(data))\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    // ensure resource version is set on the object we load from etcd\n    if err := versioner.UpdateObject(obj, uint64(rev)); err != nil {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failure to version api object (%d) %#v: %v\", rev, obj, err)\n    }\n    return obj, nil\n}\n```\n\n**Key line 397**: `versioner.UpdateObject(obj, uint64(rev))` - This sets the resourceVersion on the object to match the DELETE event's revision, regardless of the object's original resourceVersion.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Test Expectations (etcd3/watcher_test.go, lines 116-121)\n\nThe test demonstrates the expected behavior:\n\n```go\nif watchTest.expectEvent {\n    expectObj := out\n    if watchTest.watchType == watch.Deleted {\n        expectObj = prevObj\n        expectObj.ResourceVersion = out.ResourceVersion  // ← Set RV to DELETE event RV\n    }\n    testCheckResult(t, i, watchTest.watchType, w, expectObj)\n}\n```\n\nWhen a DELETE event is received, the object sent should be the previous object (prevObj) with its resourceVersion updated to the current DELETE event's resourceVersion (out.ResourceVersion).\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n**Watch Cache Filtering (cacher.go):**\n- Filters events based on whether both current and previous objects pass the watcher's filter\n- On DELETE, sends the PrevObject with the same resourceVersion as the delete event (stored in watchCacheEvent)\n\n**ETcd3 Watcher (etcd3/watcher.go):**\n- Correctly handles DELETE events by decoding the old object (prevValue) with the DELETE event's revision number\n- Calls `versioner.UpdateObject()` to set the resourceVersion to the DELETE event's revision\n- This ensures deleted objects in watch events always show the current resourceVersion, not their original one\n\nThis design allows clients receiving DELETE events to see the last known state of the object (PrevObject) with the current resource version, enabling proper cache invalidation and event ordering."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9acb4ca3-911a-4067-a3ba-399174a3a531","uuid":"927b2bc6-c0ce-4bae-b620-05c1fbb8f130","timestamp":"2026-03-31T21:47:26.462Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Search the Kubernetes codebase for watch cache filtering logic related to DELETE events and resourceVersion handling. I need to find:\n\n1. The watch cache filtering code - look for files like `pkg/storage/cacher/watch_cache.go`, `pkg/storage/cacher/cacher.go`, or similar\n2. The etcd3 watcher code that correctly handles resourceVersion on DELETE events\n3. Any code that sends PrevObject on DELETE events without updating resourceVersion\n\nKey files to look at:\n- `pkg/storage/cacher/` directory\n- `pkg/storage/etcd3/` directory  \n- `vendor/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/` directory\n\nSearch for:\n- \"PrevObject\" and how it's used in watch events\n- \"DELETE\" event handling in watch/cacher code\n- resourceVersion being set on delete events\n\nPlease read the relevant files and show me the key code sections, especially:\n1. Where the watch cache filters events and sends DELETE events with PrevObject\n2. Where etcd3 correctly sets resourceVersion on DELETE events\n\nUse Sourcegraph MCP tools if available, otherwise look in the local filesystem at the paths mentioned.\n\nActually, the instructions say \"Local source files are not present in /workspace. You MUST use Sourcegraph MCP tools for all code access.\" So please use the Sourcegraph MCP tools to search the code.\n\nSearch for these patterns:\n- \"PrevObject\" in watch cache code\n- resourceVersion handling in DELETE events\n- The watch cache filtering/filtering logic\n\nThe codebase version is Kubernetes v1.9.1.","agentId":"aa86da86562b18108","agentType":"Explore","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information needed. Let me create a comprehensive summary:\n\n## Search Results: Kubernetes Watch Cache Filtering and DELETE Event Handling\n\nBased on my analysis of the Kubernetes v1.9.1 codebase, here are the key files and code sections related to watch cache filtering logic and DELETE event handling with resourceVersion:\n\n### Key Files Located\n\n1. **/workspace/kubernetes/staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/watch_cache.go** - Core watch cache event structure\n2. **/workspace/kubernetes/staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher.go** - Cache watcher filtering and event sending\n3. **/workspace/kubernetes/staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/watcher.go** - ETcd3 watcher with correct resourceVersion handling\n\n---\n\n## 1. Watch Cache Event Structure (watch_cache.go, lines 45-61)\n\nThe `watchCacheEvent` struct includes both current and previous object information:\n\n```go\ntype watchCacheEvent struct {\n    Type                 watch.EventType\n    Object               runtime.Object\n    ObjLabels            labels.Set\n    ObjFields            fields.Set\n    ObjUninitialized     bool\n    PrevObject           runtime.Object\n    PrevObjLabels        labels.Set\n    PrevObjFields        fields.Set\n    PrevObjUninitialized bool\n    Key                  string\n    ResourceVersion      uint64\n}\n```\n\nThe watchCacheEvent stores the ResourceVersion once (the event's RV) but also maintains the PrevObject for filtering purposes.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Watch Cache Filtering Logic (cacher.go, lines 874-894)\n\nThe **sendWatchCacheEvent** function handles the filtering of watch events for individual watchers:\n\n```go\n// NOTE: sendWatchCacheEvent is assumed to not modify <event> !!!\nfunc (c *cacheWatcher) sendWatchCacheEvent(event *watchCacheEvent) {\n    curObjPasses := event.Type != watch.Deleted && c.filter(event.Key, event.ObjLabels, event.ObjFields, event.ObjUninitialized)\n    oldObjPasses := false\n    if event.PrevObject != nil {\n        oldObjPasses = c.filter(event.Key, event.PrevObjLabels, event.PrevObjFields, event.PrevObjUninitialized)\n    }\n    if !curObjPasses && !oldObjPasses {\n        // Watcher is not interested in that object.\n        return\n    }\n\n    var watchEvent watch.Event\n    switch {\n    case curObjPasses && !oldObjPasses:\n        watchEvent = watch.Event{Type: watch.Added, Object: event.Object.DeepCopyObject()}\n    case curObjPasses && oldObjPasses:\n        watchEvent = watch.Event{Type: watch.Modified, Object: event.Object.DeepCopyObject()}\n    case !curObjPasses && oldObjPasses:\n        watchEvent = watch.Event{Type: watch.Deleted, Object: event.PrevObject.DeepCopyObject()}\n    }\n    // ... send watchEvent to client\n}\n```\n\n**Key behavior on DELETE**: When an object no longer passes the filter (line 892), the watcher sends a DELETE event with the **PrevObject** (line 893). This is the old object before the filter stopped matching it.\n\n---\n\n## 3. ETcd3 Watcher - Correct ResourceVersion on DELETE Events (etcd3/watcher.go)\n\nThe etcd3 watcher correctly handles resourceVersion on DELETE events in two places:\n\n### Location A: prepareObjs function (lines 351-379)\n\n```go\nfunc (wc *watchChan) prepareObjs(e *event) (curObj runtime.Object, oldObj runtime.Object, err error) {\n    if !e.isDeleted {\n        data, _, err := wc.watcher.transformer.TransformFromStorage(e.value, ...)\n        curObj, err = decodeObj(wc.watcher.codec, wc.watcher.versioner, data, e.rev)\n    }\n    // We need to decode prevValue, only if this is deletion event or\n    // the underlying filter doesn't accept all objects (otherwise we\n    // know that the filter for previous object will return true and\n    // we need the object only to compute whether it was filtered out\n    // before).\n    if len(e.prevValue) > 0 && (e.isDeleted || !wc.acceptAll()) {\n        data, _, err := wc.watcher.transformer.TransformFromStorage(e.prevValue, ...)\n        // Note that this sends the *old* object with the etcd revision for the time at\n        // which it gets deleted.\n        oldObj, err = decodeObj(wc.watcher.codec, wc.watcher.versioner, data, e.rev)\n    }\n    return curObj, oldObj, nil\n}\n```\n\n**Critical detail** (line 374): The oldObj is decoded with `e.rev` - the DELETE event's revision number.\n\n### Location B: decodeObj function (lines 382-400)\n\n```go\nfunc decodeObj(codec runtime.Codec, versioner storage.Versioner, data []byte, rev int64) (_ runtime.Object, err error) {\n    obj, err := runtime.Decode(codec, []byte(data))\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    // ensure resource version is set on the object we load from etcd\n    if err := versioner.UpdateObject(obj, uint64(rev)); err != nil {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failure to version api object (%d) %#v: %v\", rev, obj, err)\n    }\n    return obj, nil\n}\n```\n\n**Key line 397**: `versioner.UpdateObject(obj, uint64(rev))` - This sets the resourceVersion on the object to match the DELETE event's revision, regardless of the object's original resourceVersion.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Test Expectations (etcd3/watcher_test.go, lines 116-121)\n\nThe test demonstrates the expected behavior:\n\n```go\nif watchTest.expectEvent {\n    expectObj := out\n    if watchTest.watchType == watch.Deleted {\n        expectObj = prevObj\n        expectObj.ResourceVersion = out.ResourceVersion  // ← Set RV to DELETE event RV\n    }\n    testCheckResult(t, i, watchTest.watchType, w, expectObj)\n}\n```\n\nWhen a DELETE event is received, the object sent should be the previous object (prevObj) with its resourceVersion updated to the current DELETE event's resourceVersion (out.ResourceVersion).\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n**Watch Cache Filtering (cacher.go):**\n- Filters events based on whether both current and previous objects pass the watcher's filter\n- On DELETE, sends the PrevObject with the same resourceVersion as the delete event (stored in watchCacheEvent)\n\n**ETcd3 Watcher (etcd3/watcher.go):**\n- Correctly handles DELETE events by decoding the old object (prevValue) with the DELETE event's revision number\n- Calls `versioner.UpdateObject()` to set the resourceVersion to the DELETE event's revision\n- This ensures deleted objects in watch events always show the current resourceVersion, not their original one\n\nThis design allows clients receiving DELETE events to see the last known state of the object (PrevObject) with the current resource version, enabling proper cache invalidation and event ordering."}],"totalDurationMs":55533,"totalTokens":47782,"totalToolUseCount":28,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":440,"cache_read_input_tokens":45508,"output_tokens":1834,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":440},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
