 server storage layer — specifically the watch cache (cacher/cacheWatcher) in k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage. The bug affects all client-go informers consuming namespace-scoped or selector-scoped watches via the API server watch cache.\",\n  \"severity\": {\n    \"level\": \"high\",\n    \"rationale\": \"Silent data consistency issue: informers (used by virtually all Kubernetes controllers, scheduler, and kubelet) may permanently miss events after a watch reconnection following a synthesized DELETE. Missing events can leave objects stuck in incorrect states indefinitely. The issue is non-deterministic and hard to detect — it only manifests when (1) an object moves out of watch scope AND (2) the watch connection drops afterward. The watch cache and etcd direct paths diverge in correctness, violating the guarantee that watch cache should be a transparent proxy for etcd.\"\n  },\n  \"root_cause\": {\n    \"file\": \"staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher.go\",\n    \"function\": \"sendWatchCacheEvent\",\n    \"line\": 893,\n    \"description\": \"When the watch cache synthesizes a DELETE event for an object that moved out of the watch filter scope (!curObjPasses && oldObjPasses), it emits event.PrevObject.DeepCopyObject() without updating the object's embedded resourceVersion to match event.ResourceVersion. Both etcd3/watcher.go (via decodeObj:versioner.UpdateObject) and etcd/etcd_watcher.go (via versioner.UpdateObject before emit) correctly stamp the current event revision onto the old object. The cacher.go code omits this step, causing informers to record a stale resourceVersion and miss subsequent events on reconnection.\"\n  },\n  \"remediation\": {\n    \"description\": \"In cacher.go:sendWatchCacheEvent, after DeepCopying PrevObject for a synthesized DELETE, call versioner.UpdateObject(obj, event.ResourceVersion) to stamp the current event's ResourceVersion onto the object before emitting. This requires passing the Cacher's versioner to cacheWatcher (which